## LiveTerminal - 2.0 features
But what if you REALLY want a live, typing terminal?
If your true goal is to let a user type live into the terminal screen while the code is running (like a real bash cloud console), you cannot use a simple Express POST request. A standard HTTP request is "one-and-done"—it can't stay open for live typing.

To build a truly live interactive terminal, you would need to implement:

WebSockets (Socket.io): To create a persistent, two-way communication pipe between the browser and your Node.js server.

Docker Streams: Instead of execAsync, your backend must spawn the Docker container as an interactive process (docker run -i) and hook into its stdin and stdout streams live.

Xterm.js: A frontend library that renders a real, working terminal window in the browser.

When the user types a key in the browser terminal, Socket.io sends that character to the backend, which pipes it straight into the running Docker container's stdin.

